42 (3) Project Based Vouchers;
43 (4) Veterans Affairs Supportive Housing Vouchers;
44 (5) Emergency Housing Vouchers; and
45 (6) Enhanced Vouchers.
46 (b)(1) A tenant may withhold rent payments or have a condition repaired or remedied
47 and may deduct the cost from a subsequent rent payment as provided in this subsection.
48 (2) The tenant's deduction for the cost of the repair or remedy shall not exceed the
49 amount of one month's rent under the lease or $500.00, whichever is greater. However,
50 if the tenant's rent is subsidized in whole or in part by a governmental agency, the
51 deduction limitation of one month's rent shall be the fair market rent for the dwelling and
52 not the rent that the tenant pays. The fair market rent shall be determined by the
53 governmental agency subsidizing the rent, or in the absence of such a determination, it
54 shall be a reasonable amount of rent under the circumstances.
55 (3) Repairs and deductions under this subsection may be made as often as necessary so
56 long as the total repairs and deductions in any one month do not exceed one month's rent
57 or $500.00, whichever is greater.
58 (c) A landlord is liable to a tenant as provided by this article if:
59 (1) The tenant has given the landlord notice to repair or remedy a condition by giving
60 such notice to the person to whom or to the place where the tenant's rent is normally paid
61 or electronically via email;
62 (2) The condition materially affects the physical health or safety of an ordinary tenant
63 or would make the dwelling place unfit for human habitation;
64 (3) The tenant has given the landlord a subsequent written notice to repair or remedy the
65 condition after a reasonable time to repair or remedy the condition following the notice
66 by sending such notice by a method specified in the lease or by a method accepted by the
67 landlord in practice, or by certified mail, return receipt requested, by registered mail, by
