68 email, or by another form of mail that allows tracking of delivery from the United States
69 Postal Service or from a private delivery service;
70 (4) The landlord has had a reasonable time to repair or remedy the condition after the
71 landlord received the tenant's notices; and
72 (5) The landlord has not made a diligent effort to repair or remedy the condition after the
73 landlord received the tenant's notice and subsequent notice.
74 (d) A tenant whose landlord is liable under this Code section may:
75 (1) Terminate the lease;
76 (2) Withhold rent payments until the condition is repaired or remedied;
77 (3) Deduct from the tenant's rent, without necessity of judicial action, the cost of the
78 repair or remedy; and
79 (4) Obtain judicial remedies.
80 (e) If the tenant chooses to withhold rent payments under this Code section, the tenant may
81 withhold rent until the repair or remedy is completed. The tenant shall pay all rent owed
82 within five business days following the date the repair or remedy is completed. The tenant
83 may not withhold rent payments that came due before the tenant notified the landlord of
84 the condition in need of repair or remedy.
85 (f) No late fee may be charged for rent properly withheld under this Code section.
86 (g) A landlord shall have a reasonable period of time to cure any condition or habitability
87 violation of a dwelling place. In determining whether a period of time is a reasonable time
88 to repair or remedy a condition, there is a rebuttable presumption that ten days is a
89 reasonable time. To rebut that presumption, several factors may be considered, including
90 but not limited to the following:
91 (1) The date on which the landlord received the notice;
92 (2) The severity and scope and nature of the condition; and
93 (3) The reasonable availability of materials and labor.
