94 (h) A request for more time from the landlord shall be in writing to the tenant before the
95 termination of the ten-day period to cure the violation. Written requests may be made in
96 several ways and may be delivered in person, via mail, or transmitted by email. A request
97 for more time shall include:
98 (1) A plan to repair the violation;
99 (2) A plan to mitigate the effects of the violation on the tenants; and
100 (3) An estimate of the amount of time required to cure the violation.
101 (i) If the landlord fails to cure the habitability violations within a reasonable time as
102 described in subsections (g) and (h) of this Code section, then the tenant shall have the right
103 to refuse to pay rent.
104 (j)(1) A landlord shall not retaliate against a tenant by taking an action because the
105 tenant:
106 (A) In good faith exercises or attempts to exercise against a landlord a right or remedy
107 granted to the tenant by the lease agreement, a municipal ordinance, or federal or state
108 law;
109 (B) Gives the landlord a notice to repair or exercise a remedy under this article;
110 (C) Complains to a governmental entity responsible for enforcing building or housing
111 codes, a public utility, or a civic or nonprofit agency, and the tenant:
112 (i) Claims a building or housing code violation or utility problem; and
113 (ii) Believes in good faith that the complaint is valid and that the violation or problem
114 occurred; or
115 (D) Establishes, attempts to establish, or participates in a tenant organization.
116 (2) A landlord shall not retaliate against a tenant by:
117 (A) Filing an eviction proceeding;
118 (B) Depriving the tenant of the use of the premises, except for reasons authorized by
119 law;
120 (C) Decreasing services to the tenant;
